 comprehension of the nature of reading, and the ways in which critical thinking has transformed our understanding of what it means to read.Readings addresses in a lively and engaging manner the varying rhythms and articulations made possible through the careful tracing of the process of critical reading which literary theory has made available."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCriticismxHistoryx20th century. 0aCriticismxHistoryy20th century. 0aCritique. 0aLecture. 0aLiteraturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aLiteraturexPhilosophy. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh1 aAlthusser, Louis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarker, Francis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarthes, Roland, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBennington, Geoffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBhabha, Homi K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBloom, Harold, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButler, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCixous, Hélène, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCritchley, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDerrida, Jacques, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarrell Krell, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFelman, Shoshana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoucault, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrey, Hans-